**Clinical Reasoning:**
Post-infectious glomerulonephritis primarily presents with nephritic syndrome featuring hematuria, hypertension, and oliguria, rather than nephrotic syndrome with large amounts of proteinuria. While it can occasionally exhibit proteinuria mimicking nephrotic syndrome, its typical hallmark is nephritic features. In contrast, FSGS, MPGN, and minimal change disease are well-established causes of nephrotic syndrome. Therefore, among the listed conditions, post-infectious glomerulonephritis is least consistent with classic nephrotic syndrome.

